<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>What happens in the money market when the Fed conducts open market purchases of government securities?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Money supply shifts right, interest rates fall</option>
            <option letter="b">Money supply shifts left, interest rates rise</option>
            <option letter="c">Money demand shifts right, interest rates rise</option>
            <option letter="d">Money demand shifts left, interest rates fall</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>When the Fed buys government securities in open market operations, it increases the money supply by putting more money into circulation. This shifts the money supply curve to the right, leading to lower equilibrium interest rates in the money market while money demand remains constant.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
